The paper deals with the k-error linear complexity of binary sequences, which is a measure of the randomness of pseudorandom sequences in stream ciphers. This topic falls under the category of information theory (cs.IT) and cryptography (cs.CR). The paper also involves the study of polynomial quotients, which is a topic in algebraic structures and algorithms (cs.DS). Additionally, the paper uses number theory concepts such as primitive roots and Fermat quotients, which fall under the category of number theory (cs.NT). Finally, the paper may also be relevant to the sub-category of computational complexity (cs.CC) as it deals with the complexity of generating pseudorandom sequences.
